      <hedline>
        <hl1>Give Stepmoms a Break</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Joan Entmacher letter disputes Kathryn Harrison's August 25 Op-Ed article on care of children by stepmothers</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Kathryn Harrison (Op-Ed, Aug. 25) cites studies by Princeton researchers finding that children living with stepmothers are likely to receive less food, health care and education than children raised by their biological mothers.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Kathryn Harrison (Op-Ed, Aug. 25) cites studies by Princeton researchers finding that children living with stepmothers are likely to receive less food, health care and education than children raised by their biological mothers.</p>
        <p>She notes that the studies ''oddly dovetail'' with the ''traditional suspicion'' of stepmothers in fairy tales, including ''Cinderella.'' But Ms. Harrison does not mention that Cinderella lived just with her stepmother and stepsisters, while the researchers studied children living with a stepmother and their biological father.</p>
        <p>Instead of focusing on stepmothers, perhaps we should also be asking what fathers are -- or are not -- doing, even for the children living with them.</p>
        <p>JOAN ENTMACHER  Washington, Aug. 28, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is vice president and director, Family Economic Security, National Women's Law Center.</p>
      </block>
